,Not Recommended,224440,28603915,"Posted: 24 December, 2016",all,Athravan,"This is difficult for me, as I rarely write negative reviews. I'm the type of person who writes a review when I really enjoy a game; but I do feel like I have enough history/experience with this game to review it and having had so many friends ask me if it was worth a purchase in the recent Winter Sale, it's easier for me to put my thoughts down coherently rather than have to explain individually why the answer isno - even with the 40% discount. This is gonna get long, so I hope you like reading. Otherwise, you probably shouldn't be in the steam review section. Or you can just read theTL:DR.Start scrolling.A Poor StartI bought this game in May 2013. This was back in the beginning days of Early Access, when we had little idea what to expect. I expected regular updates and what was advertised; but I think like many who bought the game back then, I was left sorely disappointed. The initial release was a bare bones poor excuse for a broken demo, with no ability to save, and a few hours of gameplay and little to no communication from the devs for the longest time.Waiting PatientlyI waited patiently, surveying patches as they came. These were incredibly slow to start with, but eventually - as the years, yes years - ticked by, as the game went on sale and I presume, as the developers obtained more funding, the game did shape up into something that's definitely playable. The game has come a long way, but even after 3.5 years of early access, it has a long long long way to go. It begins to beg the question how long is too long? What is unreasonable? On the one hand I appreciate developers not abandoning a game that clearly doesn't have the funding to be completed promptly - on the other, should they have taken my money in the first place without explaining how long a project was being funded?History Aside - What the game is todayBut I don't think it's fair to rate a game positive or negative based on yesterday. I recently reinstalled after 6 months+ of not looking at it, and the rating of this review is based on what the game is today, in Alpha 29, as if I'd just purchased it and holy mega batman balls this game has CHANGED significantly from the beginning. Everything from the core design and artwork and writing - it looks like a completely different game. So I'm swallowing the bitter pill of 3.5 years of waiting and throwing myself into what is ultimately, my favourite genre, a game-starved genre that I will eagerly buy anything in. Psst, don't tell my husband I said that, he says I have too many games. How is 1050 too many, it's not even over 9000!Strategy / BuildingThe surface allows you to real time build your village and set up supply chains. This is what I really love; my favourite genre. It's pretty standard to be honest for this sort of game. You chop wood and turn it into firewood, you catch fish and eat them, you shoot animals and build a butcher. You reap wheat and turn it into bread. The problem is, this is a very standard supply chain feature for a strategy game. It does not have even half the depth of for example, The Settlers series. It's very very simple, and currently, it seems incredibly easy. 30 minutes into a game I had hundreds and hundreds of fish mounting up every tick. My villagers were set forever. Even if you set them at max food for max happiness; the food chain supply is incredibly easy to overstock on.The buildings can be upgraded and that's a neat feature; and you can research plans and upgrades, which does add a little depth to the overhead map. On the whole though, I see no advantage to playing this over The Settlers if you want a supply chain game. Yeah, even the most recent one (7) which wasn't amazing. I feel like people looking for this sort of genre are looking for a lot more challenge and depth to their strategy, and this light-version doesn't scratch my itch for that at all, but does have potential for the future, if the buildings were vastly expanded and balance was approached.ARPG Style Dungeon CrawlerSo you get story and quests in the campaign and you take your player controlled champions to various dungeons to fight and loot. You can equip a wide range of armor and weapons and there is a decent amount of enemies and environments currently implemented. This gives the game a really nice dual-aspect. You can level up and assign some basic stats, very RPG-lite but certainly an unusual feature in a building game. Strategy/management on the surface, and then action and loot in the dungeons. That's a great idea, but only if it's actually implemented well... yeah, you can see the next part coming can't you...The Skill UI is impossible to use effectively. You have a party of heroes with unique abilities. These are pretty cool abilities, each champ is special and brings something new. But you can only select one. You can't pause, and you can't queue up abilities, and you can't switch between heroes effectively. So you basically have one character you can use, and the rest of the party is auto attacks. Why give us so many great abilities and then not give us the ability to switch between them in a meaningful way? The UI is also lacking. If it had a hotkey bar where you could set your skills it would be significantly improved. As it is you have to mouse click around the champion icon.The idea is fantastic; the current implementation is frustrating.There is no PauseThe game needs a pause. It needs it desperately. Even when you are on the build menu, the game does not pause. Your villages are doing things, including getting attacked and dying, whilst you scroll through a menu trying to decide what to upgrade, research or build. We're in management. Just pause it! How can you have real time management with no ability to manage constructively when stuff is happening.Writing & StorylineThe writing is tongue in cheek sarcastic. It attempts to be witty, but honestly, it's tiresome. At first I thought the tutorial was entertaining, but the truth is after the first few instructions about Bob, it became eye-rolling. The entire game is written in a very light hearted fantasy-trope manner. And I guess that's okay, it's a certain style, and certainly some of the writing is very witty and sarcastic. But it also detracts from immersion when it's constant. I  do think this type of writing is better when peppered in with seriousness; such as The Stanley Parable or Portal 2 - games that managed a witty and sarcastic sense of narration and humour but also built character and depth to the story. This is all surface waffle in exactly the same style throughout.It's not a bad story though at it's core, I just think that the style should be used more sparingly and the game should try and take itself a bit more seriously to give the humour more impact. Personal preference, perhaps others will love the goofy writing.Okay, I think that explains why when my friends ask me if they should purchase in the sale; my answer is still no.TL:DR I'm currently pregnant, and to be honest my kid will probably have chance to play this game before it's fully released based on the current timeline. Things progress, but it feels like nothing is really implemented to the maximum of it's potential, and overall this game sits securely in the realm of the mediocre. Great concepts as tested in Alpha 29; but there are too many flaws that make this game frustrating and ultimately, not fun. In short; keep an eye on it, but spend your money on something else right now.Note: I do update early access game reviews. I will come back to this game, although likely not for another 6 months, and we'll see where we are then. In the past I have completely rewritten reviews, and I'll keep an open mind for the future... but developers should be aware that people who have supported this game for 3.5 years may not posess an unlimited amount of patience."
76561198017065468,Not Recommended,224440,22807144,"Posted: 5 May, 2016",all,Jorrrrrn,"-----FOLK TALE REVIEW ANNUAL UPDATE BONANZA 2017-----I bought Folk Tale within about the first week that it was available on Steam. I thought it looked like a cool concept, and I had no idea that the trailer was actually the entire scope of the game back then. In the time that this game's been in Early Access, I:* Finished a Master's Degree* Moved to a new city* Moved to another new city* Held three different jobs (CORRECTION: 4 AND I KINDA LIKE MY NEW ONE)* Witnessed the birth of four children among my friends' families* Developed a hernia* Had enough time for the hernia to heal without surgery* Bought a new computer (CORRECTION: AND UPGRADED MY VIDEO CARD TWICE)* Beat The Witcher 3* Beat The Witcher 3 AGAIN (CORRECTION: INCLUDING ALL DLC)* Read 14 different books (CORRECTION: 15) (CORRECTED CORRECTION: 29)* Watched approximately 1000 sunsets (CORRECTION: 1400)* Deleted 20 duplicates of some crazy French stalker's comments on this review. Mon Dieu!* Went from nonproficiency to intermediate/advanced proficiency with the violin* Learned to read Classical Chinese* Drank approximately 1000 liters of generic cola* Happily witnessed 10 other Early Access games I purchased reaching completionPro Tip: Wait for them to finish it, then maybe take another look. (CORRECTION: RUN AWAY!)Edit: (May 2015)To be clear, before anyone throws the other obvious argument at me... Yes, I have played the game since those early weeks and, yes, it has advanced since then. But progress has been limited, and at this pace Folk Tale is more likely to die a slow death than ever realize the charming vision it had when it first came to Steam.I've already paid for it, so I'll certainly give it another look from time to time to see if anything ever becomes of it, but the whole premise of this review is that this game's a terrible risk compared to most other Early Access titles. What exists right now is still a bit of a mess, and not worth the price, and there's a very good chance that that's all you'll ever get for your money. Anyone who doesn't already have money riding on it should definitely wait.I'm not wishing doom on Games Foundry, and I'll eat my own words if they ever manage to turn this ship around, but... don't put money on that, either.Edit #2: (June 2016)In my continued drive to live at 3.82x the speed of Early Access development, I just finished another book..... ""A Great and Terrible King: Edward I and the Forging of Britain"" by Marc Morris. Lots of fascinating historical anecdotes, and Morris is also an incredible narrator.Edit #3: (July 2016)Three of Folk Tale's most loyal minions went through and downvoted... every single review I've ever written, even ones that no one had ever voted on before. I would like to thank these brave heroes for taking the time to read my previously-unnoticed reviews.Edit #4: (July 2017)TEH PROPHECY IS FULFILLED! Nothing more to see here, ladies and gents--just gotta avert our eyes for 6 months while they ""try"" to restart development (read: rebrand their studio and/or flee the country).Sometimes I hate being right. In this case I'd say I feel pretty good."
