76561198048417808,Not Recommended,224440,30224572,Posted: 27 February,all,ROFLwut?,"This game is a mess and I'm going to tell you why it's a mess, in detail. Unlike the forum fans and positive reviewers, none of whom dare talk specifics, I'm not going to blow smoke up your♥♥♥♥♥with generalizations, praise for the game's potential and emotional pleas to be nice to a developer that doesn't deserve it.This is Folk Tale as of July 3, 2017, up to date and accurate, after 4 years of alpha EA and 6 total years of development:MAP DESIGN:There's no random map generator nor are there plans to implement one. The game's replayability relies on tons of people buying the game and using the map editor to upload maps. Out of the 100k+ people that own this game, only 3 people have bothered to upload anything to the workshop in the editor's ~2 years of life, creating a total of 9 workshop items. The max map size is also tiny.Today, after 4 years, there's only 3 sandbox maps in the game. All 3 are tiny, they're all scripted, you (and everything else) spawn onto them in exactly the same spot everytime, and you're restricted to building on only a very small area of them, i.e., even the so-called sandbox portion is exactly the same every time you play it. Building area is restricted because: A. the building footprints are huge and you can only build on ground that's 100% flat, B. the map designs are awful and outside your spawn point there's almost nowhere that's flat enough to build on, and C. respawning map creeps will destroy everything outside of your alotted build area if you try to build outside of it.At least one, reportedly two, of the entire 3 sandbox maps are useless because every tree you replant explodes upon maturing, running you out of wood to build and make firewood with. Game over for anything you do on these maps.AI:Unbelievably bad!. It's basically broken and has been for 4 years. Your villagers may or may not fight back when they get attacked by something. Usually they just stand there and let themselves get killed.Military units will fight if you set them to aggressive but only if they're attacked or a mob gets in very close proximity to them, and I do mean close. Other than that, they only stand there, even if a villager is getting killed 5 feet away from them. You can't assign patrols to them either. They just... stand there and putting archers in towers is useless. You can put 4 of them in one tower and more often than not they won't attempt to kill something right below them. A single wolf will kill villagers, one after another, directly in front of a guard tower with 4 archers in it and they will do NOTHING! This isn't a rare occurence either, it's typical behavior.Any villager with a job that makes them roam will walk right up to any mob on the map like it's not even there. They'll walk right into a pack of wolves, bears or spiders and ignore it when it attacks them. They don't even try to run away.LEVEL SCALING:Map creeps are designed to level up with your heros, so if you're off doing stuff with them the mobs level as they do. This makes all the mobs on the map way over the level of your regular villagers. A single mob can walk into your town and kill every single person in it with just 1 or 2 hits. Even if you have 200 people in it, that 1 mob is easily capable of killing them all if you don't get your hero or a pack of military units there to stop it. Why? Because it's level 10 but all your townies, including your military units, are 3 or 4.MANAGEMENT:What management? You build buildings and assign people to them but there is no way to quickly determine who works where or how many are doing this or that job. You have to click on each building to find this out and then do the math yourself.People are almost impossible to see and even harder to select. If you want to move one person for whatever reason, more often than not you grab half a dozen others along with them because it's far easier to just drag a box over them than trying to click on them singly. There are control groups for military units but no way to locate them quickly once you select one.Villagers without jobs only stand in packs in front of their houses. They have no use other than being spider food. They don't transfer things around town or even wander about. They occasionally go get some firewood or something but that's it. They're supposed to put out fires but... well, more on that later.DESIGN CONCEPTS:Horrible! You want to plant carrots? You need a windmill. Why? I have no idea. There's no farmers in Folk Tale, only millers, and all fields are restricted to a circular radius around a windmill, weaver or herbalist hut.Woodcutters chop trees, make firewood and cut planks but you can't control their outputs. They also replant trees but they don't do it at a 1:1 ratio so they constantly run out of trees and just stand there until the few they did replant mature, then it's back to standing around again. This is a chronic problem.Resource ticks constantly float up from every building and person in the game. Your screen will be filled with it all the time and it looks awful. Probably not helping the framerate either.Certain things like village raids and abandonment have been a problem for years and the developer has been unable to fix them so they've added checkboxes (gameplay customization... LMAO!) in the settings to turn these mechanics off completely.COMBAT:Boring, amateur and poorly implemented. Nothing else to say about it.RESEARCH:Only tier 1 is implemented for anything and that's only like a few +1 output type deals and a radius expansion. Some buildings are still lacking even tier 1.CRAFTING:Only trivial implementation.DEVELOPMENT PROGRESS:Other than hitting EA in 2013 with an expected release in 2014 but still in alpha in 2017 and development now suspended until ""the end of the year"", the best example of this circus is: After 3 months of experimental patches, fires was released in the latest public patch and it's broken. Loading a save causes half the town to instantly burst into flames and nobody does anything about it. 3 months of experimental patches and it's always this way. Aside from that, public patches are ~1 per 3 months and fixes (actual fixes) are rare. Most updates are content-related and almost always hacked in either poorly designed, extremely unbalanced or just plain broken. Oftentimes the problems they try to fix are only made worse.THE DEVELOPER HIMSELF:No idea what he's doing. He listens to a small handful of people that tell him what he wants to hear and that's it. Tell them they're going to slow or something is bad and the fans all pile in to shout you down. Refuse to be and you get banned. He has no vision for this game and no idea how to do the things he's trying to do, which is more than evident by playing the mess that's it's taken them 4 years to deliver.Amazing hypocrite and seems to have an emotional hair trigger. Read his selectively enforced forum guidelines. You will find one that makes deleting his comments FROM YOUR REVIEW a bannable FORUM offense. He added this rule to ban a single poster, whom he banned the same day, that otherwise hadn't broken a single forum rule.He banned me when I called out a guy for lying about the game in his review. He defended the liar and banned me for telling the truth. He allows his fans to lie right through their teeth, attack critical posters endlessly and break any other forum rule they please without so much as a warning but will ban a critic at the 1st opportunity, even if he has to concoct BS rules to justify it. This is a constant thing with this developer.THE ""COMMUNITY"":Bunch of liars, all of them. Aside from the developer they're the main ones responsible for the failure of this game. Never have you seen such shameless dishonesty. Read the comments to find some copy/pasted examples plus some lies being told here directly."
