,Not Recommended,224440,7804281,"Posted: 28 November, 2013",all,yrg,"Folk Tale has been available since the 30. May 2013, and since the release very little has changed aside from bugfixes and the addition of a savegame feature. In my opinion the game was released on Steam too early.It has a very nice art style and the concept for it looks great - but the available playable content is very, very limited.The plan is for this to be a sandbox experience type of game with stuff like building your own town, crafting, sieges, characters that gain experience and equip items that monsters on the map/in dungeons drop, and much more. Together with the overall graphical/sound quality of the game and the chosen theme, this would make for a great experience.But only a tutorial for one of the races is available for now, and even though the developers are commited to communication and bugfixes, the available content does not warrant the purchase of the game at the time of writing this - 28 November 2013. There is also no set date for the release of new content to the game.You can read blog posts and news about what the developers eventually plan to add to the game here:http://blog.gamesfoundry.com/"
76561198030061912,Recommended,224440,19759097,"Posted: 17 December, 2015",all,Zardain,"If you want to see the game, watch the videos. My opinion is that it has a solid foundation now and has already begun implementing many of the big items that many of us have been waiting for. I have read a lot of negative reviews like anybody else looking at a mixed review game and there are many older reviews that really did make sense at the time they were posted, but this is now and that was then.The game?In short...Your the hero looking for treasure chests, killing enemies, and progressing through a story. Your also the one controlling the growth of the town, building walls, and making troops to travel with the hero and guard the town. However, the game is made so you can set up your town and use a summary to see whats needed or if anything is. That leaves you free to focus on your hero at times without your town falling apart. Make sure you have guards though.Few more details...The game looks just like the videos, smooth and tranquil. Your townspeople walk everywhere to do their job. (transport goods, plant trees, hunt animals, eat, etc.) So you will not see somebody working a farm non-stop and you gather food over time. It is easy to get caught up watching your people and forget that you need to clear our enemies from a nest or go look for treasure chests. Do not be fooled though. Enemies are hard and your hero is not an unstoppable force. Nests and such also grow over time if not destroyed. That means larger numbers and can quickly wipe out everything you have worked for. You should also make or find better equipment for your hero, guards, and citizens. Don't want to micro manage? Make the gear, move it to your inventory, put it into the citizens place of employment, and they will equip it if they can. There is a lot more than just your city building and townspeople. (i.e. story line, settements, other heros, etc.) I will let the videos, images, and devs cover the rest.The devs?In short...Watch a recorded live feed to get a feel for them. They will look at and test things simply because a player mentions it. So yes, they work very close to the players. You can see the peer to peer communication in the live feeds all the time. Updates are pushed out as quickly as possible and content is always being adjusted to find the best settings, look, and/or feel.In detail...Do you think the game is how it is now because the devs said it will be this way? If so, you are wrong. Countless things have been adjusted because of player comments and many times they are tested on the spot during a live stream. The devs are normally guys. They do talk to people but they do not talk down to people. Some of the reason things move slower than you may like is because the devs are working so close with the players to revise anything from NPC spawn rates to graphics, but don't be shocked if they say no."
76561198087300008,Recommended,224440,19373717,"Posted: 29 November, 2015",all,mafilux,"When I first purchased Folk Tale a couple years back I thought it showed some great promise with it's concept - a fun city builder with a few RPG elements thrown in. I played it for a couple hours and thought to myself: ""Well I supported the project, I guess I'll just wait and let the developers work."" I have not been disappointed with the progress that has been made coming back to it a couple years later.Building is rather enjoyable and watching your town grow into a bustling city is a rewarding experience. As your city grows you're constantly devising ways to improve people's 'happiness' by offering more rations or creating new jobs to keep the populace content and working away. All of the jobs work and the villagers carry out their tasks with little prodding from the player, allowing you to focus on city planning and defending. The jobs themselves are varied and all play a role in how well your city will run. There are also research trees for each profession to improve productivity or expand the area in which they will work.There is a fair amount of building options to make for some interesting town ideas. Buildings are also upgradeable to improve their capacity as well, allowing the player to go for a more minimalist approach if they so desire. Many of the structures work in tandem with others (A hunting lodge will have villagers collect meat, but in order to feed that meat to your citizens you must also build a butcher, etc). I like the idea of this because it makes the player have to do a small bit of planning in order to maximize efficiency of these professions. The buildings are all unique as well and visually different so smart building placement allows for some beautiful looking towns and cities. You can also place buildings nearly everywhere and rotate them as you see fit, allowing lots of freedom in where you want your town to be located as well as how you want it to look.As for the game itself: The UI is simple and easy to get into. There are tooltips for beginners that explains what each building does, and what other buildings compliment them so that they work properly. You can also assign jobs to individuals without having to click each villager and send them off to the proper buildings, and it's easy to switch a villager from one profession to the next. There is also some layer of complexity with the research and upgrading systems, to allow players some freedom in which areas of production they wish to improve. Everything works great and I have experienced very few bugs outside of a single crash on the tutorial, which worked later when I tried again. The game runs great and is very stable for an alpha build, and it's optimized well and has no frame rate issues.The heroes portion of the game breaks the mould a bit as you can use them to go adventuring. You can also train some soldiers to aid your heroes along in whichever endeavours you want them to have, adding a sort of real time strategy feel to the game. The heroes also have unique abilities and can even be fully equipped from head to toe with various armors and weapons (As can every villager or soldier in the game), allowing the player to make them as strong or weak as you want.All in all Folk Tale is a lot of fun, and I can't wait to see what's in store for the future of the game."
,Recommended,224440,20184242,"Posted: 1 January, 2016",all,ViperZeroOne,"(TL:DR at the bottom)PrefaceWhen I normally see a new game that interests me, the first thing I do is check out the reviews.  With a title labeled as “mixed” the first place I usually jump over to is the negative reviews and see what people are saying.  This game, with its “mixed” rating, was no different.  I saw claims that the development team wasn’t active, they were bullying people on the forums, and the game had almost no content to it.  Something to be avoided, right?  But I noticed something else.  On many of the negative reviews the developers had replied and tried to help resolve the reviewer’s problems.  That doesn’t seem like bullying to me, and certainly doesn’t seem like they aren’t active.  So I went and checked the positive reviews.  The top one was written by a fellow named “Eddie=VX9=” and pretty much his first statement was that you shouldn’t judge this game based on the negative reviews.  I continued to read his review and was fairly impressed by its content.  This led me to risk purchasing the game.  Do I regret that decision?  Obviously not.ReviewWhen I first jumped into Folk Tale I have to admit, it wasn’t a positive experience.  But it was my fault.  I’m a regular player of RTS games and figured this was just like any other so I selected to start a new campaign.  Big mistake.  The story began and I immediately realized I hadn’t a clue how to play.  Sure, I was able to grab some units and defend the village.  I was able to get a few people foraging for berries and wood.  But I didn’t understand how the buildings worked.  I had tons of meat but my villagers were leaving the village because, I later found, there was nobody turning that meat into something actually edible.  I didn’t have a butcher!  So my first shot at the campaign ended in under 20 minutes with my villagers abandoning me.  Yay team!I then went back to the main menu, clicked new game, and sheepishly clicked Tutorial.  Within another 20 minutes I had learned everything I needed to learn to give the campaign another go.  It turned out to be a fairly easy task to assign (or remove) villagers to buildings, although a little different than other RTS games.  Once I had the basics figured out, the campaign called me once more.  This time I had everything under control and really started to enjoy the game.  I found that this wasn't only an RTS experience, it has a bit of RPG dungeon crawling to it as well.  Quite a nice experience overall.Admittedly I haven’t tried the sandbox mode yet.  I assume it's basic village building with random attacks.  I can imagine that would be an enjoyable experience.  There's also the in-game map/misison creator which gives you pretty much endless replayability in this title, and I'm heavily looking forward to messing around with it.  I did notice there wasn't any multiplayer, and I wish there was, but there is so much else available that it really isn't a big loss.Now, let’s get down to the nitty gritty.Graphically, I absolutely love this game.  I really don’t know what to compare it to because I haven’t seen any RTS games with this style of graphics.  It’s almost Disney-like, if that’s a word, with overtones from the Settlers series.  You can look at the screenshots and game play videos for yourself.  I would have liked to see better animations on buildings being constructed, like maybe showing them in different phases of construction instead of the completed building simply rising through the ground.  That’s not a major complaint though.Audio in the game was fairly well done, and I love the music, but I have some reservations when it comes to voiceovers.  Much of the campaign dialogue has voiceovers but you’ll have some instances where it almost seemed like a voiceover was missing.  A quick example would be the start of the campaign where the villain was talking to his henchmen and, while his voiceover was awesome, the henchmen had nothing but a text box.  It almost seemed like the henchmen’s voiceover was missing, which it could be considering this is still an early access game.  A game should either have full voiceovers, or none at all.  I’d like to see that corrected before final release.Game play itself is rather well thought out in Folk Tale.  A lot of the villager control is handled by an AI, which can surprisingly be turned off (per unit) if you want.  You simply assign the villager to a building (promote) and they go about the job without any further action on your part.  When you remove a villager from that task (demote) they return to a simple villager and do the “grunt work” around the village.  These villagers are your builders and resource carriers, but can also be assigned to other tasks like berry foraging and tree chopping without being assigned to a building (job).  You also have control of the distribution of materials as well as collection of taxes.  These help you fine tune the happiness of your villagers and can also help get you through tough times without your village becoming a ghost town.  The effect is limited, in that if you have no food increasing the amount of food a villager receives obviously won't have any effect.  You also have the RPG aspect, which means not only do your main (hero) units level up and get stat points, but you can also equip all of your units (including villagers).  Equipment is mostly found by either defeating enemies or forraging through the various dungeons (like the bandit cave).TL:DR & ConclusionAll in all I have to agree with the excellent review that “Eddie=VX9=” did.  This game may have had problems in the past but it’s well on its way to becoming a game that any RTS fan would love to have.  The RPG aspects mixed in with the RTS makes it a wonderful experience.  I'll admit this game may not be for everyone, but it's a game I'm glad to have in my collection.Note To The DevsYou're doing a great job, the whole team, and I don't want you to get discouraged by some of the negative reviews this game is getting.  Honestly, most of the negative reviews are either way outdated or absolute nonsense.  I can see the road you've laid down and I, as well as others, are very excited to see the work continue.  Keep it up!  This game has a ridiculous amount of potential in both the game itself and the community it can build around it.  It deserves to be finished, even if it's just to prove the nay-sayers wrong.  Once it's done you might even consider raising the price a little, because it'll be worth it.  Keep your chins up and speak proudly about this game when you do.  Here's to the future!  :beermug:"
