76561198007981328,Not Recommended,224440,26478355,"Posted: 7 November, 2016",all,Fallow,"Summary: Great ideas and excellent writing with longstanding balance issues and poorly implemented RTS controls.Pros: Excellent writing in the tutorial, quests, dialogue. Very good job and very funny with lots of funny references to find. Tells a fun story and makes you want to play all the quests.Graphics are pleasing and interface is decent.Cons: Poor implementation on balance and controls.Balance:Far too many spider attacks even on easy mode. What happens is this, villagers are assigned to work buildings. When a spider kills a villager the building he was working at produces less and when this happens enough of the overall village happiness drops to the point villagers start leaving. This causes a snowball effect where leaving villagers drop the happiness rate faster and faster and the only way to increase it is to assign more villagers to those buildings which you don't have because they are all leaving.  This is very frustrating and unfun.  I restarted a few times on standard and a once on easy. In each case the game was tons of fun at first sliding into a frustrating job of micromanaging spider attacks and eventual village death.  I was so busy micromanaging I couldn't pursue the very enjoyable quests.Controls: The game plays like a Realtime Strategy and city sim. It lacks the standard RTS controls however making it difficult to manage 30+ villagers at a time when they die so often to spider attacks.  There is no option I saw to set a rally point for produced troops.  No queue for multiple orders or waypoints.  You can set a particular building to 'auto-fill' positions with villagers but it always fills to max. I would have liked to set it to only 1 villager as a baker for instance rather than the max of 4.   You get attacked from multiple directions as well so it would be nice to set a guard point and have the barracks automatically train new villagers as soldiers and send them to the guard point to replace losses.I always consider how long a game has been in development and check if they have any outstanding issues that have persisted for a long time without the devs resolving them.It seems from the other comments and reviews that there are many such long-standing issues with Folk Tale so I don't recommend this for anything above $10 until they have adjusted the spider spawn rate at the very least.Also: The tutorial was so funny and engaging that I forgot I was making breakfast and I burned my toast."
