,Not Recommended,224440,34148491,Posted: 10 August,all,eXophobia,"(tldr at the bottom)The start:Bought game very soon after it came to Steam Early Access.Had high hopes for the game concept (Settlers with minor Hero/RPG elements). Team responded very well initially to community feedback and after a long hiatus (almost a year for all I remember) they resurfaced with a polished playable Alpha and a new design road based on community feedback (Primarily sandbox gameplay + randomised quest system in favor of a campaign).How it went on:Over the years they chose to drop more and more features - quite understandably as they just couldn't meet their goals (initial timeline was set to at max 2 years Early Access).First they introduced way more hero related stuff than I had ever expected or was announced. Settlement economy wasn't working at all at the time, lacked alot of content - there wasn't even hostile monsters yet. But at least we got one, then two and then three distinctive heroes with their own personalities and beginning storylines.Then they dropped the idea that players could enter buildings, next they dropped that feature completely (customizable housing).Fast forward a few years. The heroes aren't really there any more and became more generic in favor of a campaign telling the story. A campaign? Yes, the sandbox questing feature wasn't received well by new EarlyAccess backers and it was decided to shift development to a campaign.By now settlements had a working economy with mediocre content and some obviously missing elements. There were guards&archers and monsters - all of it working. But not much more than that. Heroes were there, but not available ingame at that moment.Fast forward a few years. The dev team announces that internal struggles are crippling their development. Additionally they can't deal with the negative feedback they keep getting on their Steam Storepage (every since the game's rating went to Mixed and below). So they announced repeatedly that they requested to suspend their store page and stop sales on Steam momentarily completely.Dear devs:* If you run out of money, that's cool. Be open about it and talk to the community.* If you run out of people to work on the project, be open about it. There are actually techies in your backers base that might help out.* Be open for discussions on how to tackle the issues about financing, release, DLC/addon packs.Here's however what not to do:* Ignore your long term backers that have been with you for many many years. Contributed to development and engaged in discussions.* Go over your long term backers in favor of new ones for what seems like money related issues.* Go on month (even year) long hiatus without ANY response at all. Just to resurface with genius ideas that ignore the community.* Blame community for giving your programming project (it's not a game after all right now) a negative feedback on the store.So yes I totally get that you dislike negative feedback. But whining about it is not the way to tackle the problem. You get those negative reviews because we don't want people to pay you for ... well what are they actually paying for? Your job? Your extra income to your regular job? Maintenance costs for your marketing, servers, rent?If you wanna change something, don't change your company's name, change your attitude. Stand up to the negative reviews, start to include the community again. As soon as things go for the better, people will start changing their reviews accordingly (you know these entries can be modified by us, right?).tldr; for new people interested in buying the game:As of now, August 2017, everything hints that the game won't be finished ever. The team is torn in internal and community struggles. They go back and forth on what part of the game they want to develop. Their current actions (past months) show the typical signs of a studio going out of business."
,Recommended,224440,21574528,"Posted: 1 March, 2016",all,George,"Folk Tale is a Fantasy village builder action role-playing game.The game is currently in early-acces.The game currently has alot of content, even though it's in early acces.The game has a sandbox mode, you can also play the Campaign.The campaign is still under development, but from what I've seen it's very promising.You start out with a group of peasants, you construct your city, your villagers have needs. of course you have to keep your villagers happy. some of the needs are: Warmth, Different sorts of food and clothing.Your villagers can gather food, wood, stone and iron. to make your villagers work more efficient you can construct buildings, such as a woodcutters hut and a Fishing hut.You can also upgrade the buildings to increase productivity.You need certain buildings to craft items for your villagers/soldiers to use.There are many sorts of buildings to construct, and the developers keep adding more!Besides the city building you can also explore the world, the game features a real-time combat system.You can manage the inventory of every individual villager.In the world there are many things to explore. such as different cultures, monsters, dungeons and many more!There is alot of contact between the developers and the community, every patch features many improvements, balancing, bug fixes, new content.If you enjoy micromanagement, city builders, story-rich, fantasy, action, RPG, adventure, crafting games you won't regret buying this amazing game!"
