,Not Recommended,224440,15849433,"Posted: 15 May, 2015",all,misguidedgh0st,"TL;DR: Followed game since before release and through patches since release. Very disappointed; game is incomplete.I purchased this game on the day of release; I followed it before it was even released on Early Access on Steam. Since then, I have kept my eye on the game as it rotted away in my Steam library. As a gamer who grew up on RTS, RPG, and Simulators, this game should be everything I desire in a game. It has so much potential; it breaks my heart in its current state. Yes, this game is beautiful. Yes, this game has endless character. But it is so very incomplete. It's early access, but that is no excuse. It has been almost two years now since release. We deserve more from this game. I would hate to see this game wind up alongside games like DayZ, known for sucking consumers in during Early Access and then providing a flop of a game. I cannot recommend this game, as much as I'd love to. If things improve, I will gladly and wholeheartedly change my review, but until then, it's a thumbs-down from me.Edit #1 (Aug. 29, 2016)I've given this game a bit more time to develop. The new campaign seems to be developing a feel similar to the classic Warcraft III, but with a good sense of humor. The characters are funny, with some references here and there. I can see a good story developing from this. Unfortunately, everything still feels clunky, even after so long. The music score is good, as are the voices and the writing. The gameplay itself is lackluster. Many features are simply unavailable, and the core gameplay leaves a lot to be desired. If combat is going to become key to the game, more combat-capable units are needed. The first part of the campaign pits your hero and some militia up against units that are far superior and will simply crush you, leaving your hero dead over and over again. The building ideas are good, and seem functional, so not much to discuss there. I'd like to see a few more facets to flesh the game out, and I know the sandbox mode definitely needs more work. I'll keep checking back every once and awhile to see where things go, but I cannot change my recommendation at this point."
