,Recommended,224440,17411120,"Posted: 6 August, 2015",all,SoundWizard™,"If you like RTS games, I can recommend Folk Tale. It's a bit of both Warcraft 3 and Settlers. Warcraft 3 because it contains an RPG element and you build structures to gain resources but Settlers, because there's a little bit micro-management with your buildings and villagers.I watch the GamesFoundry stream on twitch every Wednesday and through that, I know they are constantly updating the game to become better. They also listen to the community and make changes if necessary.Which was evident from the start when the game wouldn't let you train female villagers into certain working roles, but people complained so they fixed it.As of this date: Aug/2015, there is no victory point. Meaning  you will play a map and it will simply never end unless you did badly. However, that'll most likely change soon.If you like to craft your own maps and give them out to a community to play, the game got a powerful and simple editor for you to mess around with. Steam workshop will be available for the game soon to facilitate map making and sharing.Finally, I would like to list some of my pros and cons:Pros-Fun game play.-Great British humor (Think modern Monty Python).-Excellent map editor.-Developers heed feedback.-Beautiful music score.-Heroes and villagers can level up.-Love the loot system and that you can give new gear to your heroes and various professions.-You can research upgrades for your buildings.Cons:-No end goal to a map yet.-Voice acting is a bit wonky and can be repetitive and annoying.-Sound design and foley is less than adequate.-No guard tower unless you build a wall which can ruin your village layout.-No story in the game, however, I know it is coming.-Professions, like the baker, will get flour and return it to the bakery and it'll automatically generate the bread. You will never see him make the bread which makes me feel like he should just be a carrier instead of a fully dressed baker.-While crafting is nice, it is a micro-management that becomes tedious for a large village, as you have to hunt down the house that can craft the item. It would be much better with a crafting tab that contained all the recipes.-You cannot set what sort of crop you want to grow until the field is complete. While minor, if you are pulled away from your field before or as it's being built, you might forget to set it to grow cotton and later on wonder why you never get any cloth bolts made."
