76561198016943128,Not Recommended,224440,29006879,Posted: 4 January,all,wrathtribe,"I bought Folk Tale at Alpha 29. I found the RTS part completely unbalanced as both settlers and soldiers alike are pretty♥♥♥♥♥♥when it comes to fighting. Melee characters like spearmen or the allegedly superior town guard can't even beat a couple of rabbits of the same level (no kidding) without major losses, and large numbers of them make little difference as collision boxes prevent (which is good) swarming a single enemy. Although I suspect major modifications will occur when game goes Beta, for now I feel like the only viable option for armies is going ranged (and kite or use terrain like rivers or cliffs as walls - since walls are out in that build) or mix (and use the melee as blocker cannon fodder).Playing a couple of games in campaign and survival mode I found out that some attacks are scripted and come from spawn points (which may at some point be right in the middle of your town). Beside the awkwardness of having some wolves spawning in the middle of your settlers and considering how weak all of your troops (including heroes) are, carnages often occur. Of course with a high morale, the losses of civilians aren't that annoying if you have auto-recruit on on your building, but for the useless soldiers it leads to you micromanaging them (as there is currently neither a rally point feature on the barracks nor the auto feature do produce anything else than the basic spearmen which you have to retrain manually).I also found out that monsters level up based on a criteria which I haven't been able to identify yet, but that I suspect to be town military strenght capacity, which may lead to game breaking situations (if you evolved your town too quickly comparatively to the leveling up of your troops and heroes, every unit will end up being one shot by monsters and - considering also the XP penalty for death - will never get a chance to level up and compete ever again) where heroes don't stand a chance to beat dungeons and where you have to kill thousands of monster with a swarm of arbalist (the only viable option) to get a chance to level your soldiers up to be more competive in small numbers). So you may find yourself in the dire situation of a very steep increase of enemy level when uncovering the fog of war of a new enemy (i.e. a spider nest) or going into a dungeon. That is a bad - and hopefully very temporary - design choice as players who will focus on upgrading their town and defense over exploring and expanding may end up in a situation where any progress is made impossible.I was at first very disappointed not to find walls, towers or anything that could actually make me compensate the lack of individual efficiency of my military units by using a bit of strategy. Alpha 29 has no walls. After some research I found out they used to be, along with several towers and, well, a major bug which may explain why they have been removed. Well, walls are essential and the new engineering turrets, while a cool addition, aren't compensating the huge necessity of having walls in this game.I was suprised that, having had Folk Tale on my wishlist since about 3 years now, the very good looking game was still so lacking in terms of polishing of the game mechanics and content. In fact, there seems to be so much remaining to do that this game may remain in Alpha for a couple more years. I understand that the scope and ambition of the game are huge, mixing all those genre from RTS, city builder, TD, RPG, MOBA, and it remains extremely promising (although as to be expected with such a hotchpotch that actually none of each element has any depth in it - i.e. the economy, while having some illusory layers of complexity is absolutely unchallenging and is extremely linear as you will always build the same things in the same order starting with one or two food sources, clothes and then mead).Still Folk Tale may end up being an entertaining game with more than decent appearance and sound (the atmosphere of the game sadly is déjà vu and overexploited for medieval cartoonish games, but that may only annoys you provided you are a veteran gamer) if it ever get finished with its actual ambitions. Considering how slow the development process was till now (despite the fact I have to acknowledge that besides the obvious placeholders and temporary features, there is a lot of polish in that game) it would be hard to believe that the final product is going to become some kind of reference unless many many years of work (or an increase in this studio's output) are assigned to this project.In its current state and considering the history of the product, I can't heartily recommend it. Though as the steam review system do not allow me to publish a neutral review, I'd like to be clear that if you understood the ambitions of developers through my or others lucid reviewers comments, if you understood there is little chance that when it will finally be released the game won't achieve some legendary status in terms of depth, strategical options and challenge (despite your settlers dying like flies) and is very likely to just be a very polished jack-of-all-trades game then it may be worth supporting, provided you are patient, or buying on release."
