76561198031481122,Recommended,224440,14433474,"Posted: 11 February, 2015",all,Fishkeeper01,"Ok, so my first review was on Feb 11, 2015. It was for a very different game from the one that currently exists. That game was essentially a tutorial that wasn't complete and couldn't be saved. And it got a negative review from me because of these things, and because of changes made that seemed to confuse the game's center. Now, however, the game is much more filled-out. I will note that this game is a LOT like The Settlers, most specifically the single Settlers game I've actually played through (6, Rise of an Empire). Not exactly a clone of the game, but definitly in the same general region of Sandbox-Campaign gaming.It's worth a play, even if it's far from complete at this time.0) Overall - 7/10 - Campaign is small but has a lot of potential if they can expand it across multiple maps and over about 12 more hours worth of space. Sandbox is fun, needs bigger maps. Combat is poor, but workable. City Building has some issues, but is overall a very fun and functional aspect of the game.1) Campaign - 5/10 - The Campaign certaintly shows promise. As of right now it's fairly short and seems to just be a number of placeholder missions to keep the Dev Team aware of what the campagn is meant to be. So while it has a decent overall plotline the campaign is short, fairly flimsy overall, and doesn't give you the impact needed for a solid game campaign. Hopefully this will be expanded as the game continues.2) Sandbox - 7/10 - I've just started playing the Sandbox mode, and so far I'm enjoying it. I won't lie and say it's perfect (it's not lol) but it is fairly fun and I do enjoy building cities and the like. They need to add some more features (roads would be nice, as would more types and teir of building) but for the most part the sandbox has no issues. [This is Subject to Change as I play through the 3 Sandbox Maps]3) Factions - 7/10 - The factions are rather unimaginative overall. Undead v Fae Folk. On the surface it's pretty bland, but if you look a little deeper you'll find that it actually has some decent points for both sides being in a Gray&Grey morality. Needs work on that aspect though - Greed v Self Defense doesn't leave much space for Gray&Grey. It would also be nice if there was a third factions (besides your own) that was fully neutral and could be interacted with. Finally, being able to create peace between the two factions would also be a nice touch.4) Combat - 4/10 - Combat is... not very pleasant to be honest. Heroes are hard to level up past a certai point, but by that same token there isn't any cost of losig a hero (or units in general for that matter). Training them doesn't have an expense, and you don't lose items when your units die in battle. If every time a hero died they lost off of their gear it would be decidedly more difficult and much more important to keep the hero alive. By that same token, if City Watch units died and lost items it would make people more careful about losing them. If that was the only issue it would be fine, however the inability for heroes to self-activate their special moves is rather annoying and leads to more deaths than is really needed. Maybe I'm just not good enough xD5) City Building - 8/10 - City building is fun. As a city builder this definitly ranks with some of the other games I've played. However, it is not without it's (rather large) assortment of flaws and weak points. The biggest of those is the complete lack of roads. Without placable roads that buildings lock to (which was/is my favorite feature in The Settlers games) city planning is a haphazard thing at best. With proper roads and road-locking players could build cities with a lot more planning and functionality than we currenty can. Another issue I have is the space needed between buildings. Granted, the games I usually play that are like this (TheSettlers & Banished) allow buildings that are rammed right up to each other and both have a well-designed road mechanic, but still. There shouldn't need to be enough space between two buildings to cram an entirely different building.6) World Map - ?/10 - This feature is only partially implemented, but oh boy do I like the look of it! If the world map does what I expect it to do, it'll enable more kinds of city, larger and smaller map sizes, and a dozen other cool features. I really hope that it means we will get to see a campaign that's spread across multiple maps with different types of landscapes and creatures to fight, trade, and otherwise interact with.7) Custom - ?/10 - Haven't tried this yet, it's on my list."
