76561198013132245,Recommended,224440,26435785,"Posted: 5 November, 2016",all,huminado,"I've only played sandbox.---- Immersion ----The game has some funny voice acting and generally very high quality artwork.  The UI looks nice.  The tone and artwork of the game remind me of Torchlight.  The voice acting was clearly done with as few voice actors as possible, some parts obviously the same person's voice - but they are really nice to listen to.  I would say this becomes a major contributor to making the game enjoyable.The maps seem to all be static (i.e. there's currently no map generator).---- City Building ----Growing population goes slowly, to make sure balance is maintained and people don't get upset and leave.  If they do get unhappy, a downward spiral can happen as resources are no longer available and more people become unhappy.  There is an initial learning curve for getting up to maybe 30 people (that felt like an accomplishment), and growth needs to be methodical and calculated to ensure stability.  Because of this balancing act, the city can also be vulnerable to the unhappiness spiral if there are attacks to key systems.Also if the downwards spiral leads to a ghost town (everyone has left) there's currently no mechanism allowing people to come back and starting over.Each building has a tech tree which pushes the anticipated game time out into relatively longish games.---- RPG hack and slash ----The connection between the hero and the town is that an army can eventually join the hero in fighting otherwise impossible opponents.  Weapons and armor can also be built in town.  This becomes a high motivation for enlarging the town, and creates the ""play a little longer"" syndrome which makes this game hard to stop playing.Each hero has special moves that burn ""special move burning delay thing"" (oh maybe it's called mana or stamina or a combo of the two: stamana... :)  lol  :)  I didn't bother reading the game manual.---- Customization ----Oh...  I almost forgot about this!  Modding capability in this game is through the roof, as they provide a full visual node-based programming system to control enemy or camera behaviors for generating cut-scenes and drama.  In fact, when I first installed the game I went straight to __the edittor__ of all things!  I was so excited to want to look at the system right away!Please look at the FAQ threads pinned at the top of the discussions for videos showing what it can do.  This means there will undoubtedly be continuous content being created by the community of players, and more than makes up for the lack of random map generator.---- Grinding ----For RPGs my favorite element is storytelling.  But you may want to cover your ears, as what I will say is not so nice - but after years and years of reading or hearing typical fiction, I don't much care for most pre-written fiction, including fantasy, and especially including canned RPG adventures.  There comes a point where it all seems so arbitrary and whimsical at the author's imagination.  The only storytelling so far in RPGs I've enjoyed are in <a different game> which is also a roguelike, and shows up in my list of games, and has the word waz in it...  But the stories in Folk Tale won't be generated at run-time randomly -- they will be the canned type, and that makes the game feel a bit grindy after a while.  I can already anticipate getting tired of it.---- Putin Jokes ----This always makes me a bit nervous.  Then again I am paranoid.  Then again, paranoid might have good reasons.  Nonetheless, it makes me a bit nervous.  But Gamesfoundry is based in England, so maybe there's nothing to worry about:http://www.gamesfoundry.com/about/developer/---- Overall -----I found this on sale at a token discount, and checked Steam price charts at some other website which showed the game's price doesn't move much.  It's a fair price, especially considering the long games and the modding capabilities, and if you really love RPGs, this might be just right for you too."
