76561198011083571,Recommended,224440,15995186,"Posted: 25 May, 2015",all,Carig,"Folk Tale is a village management game which combines a sandbox “Stronghold” style settlement management system with a story driven scenario manager. The game is in early access. The basic settlement management system works now and there is 5 maps to play on.Pros- It's beautiful graphics create a lovely atmosphere- It's  fun to play now. I have had about 18 hours of play out of Alpha 20. Alpha 21 came out yesterday (roughly a month after alpha 20) so I will see how play I can get from that.- It has some intriguing build tools for making both maps and scenarios.- Being part of the development process itself is quite fun. Games Foundry goes out of its way to keep the community informed about progress.- The village mechanics with tiered buildings, villager experience, a village tech tree are great (although still in the process of being adding to and balanced).- The concept is a good one, and basic way it is being implemented is far sighted. They have designed mechanics for village simulation, character progression,  and story mode. They have made editors to create maps and scenarios. They reworked their game concept to based on a sandbox simulation (which I get the feeling was not the original plan) and did this successfully. They have been doing this for 2 years and just keep at it… this game will be finished and be an impressive beast at the end.Cons- The game has been developed in full view on early access for most of its life. This gives the impression of a ""slow"" development pace. If this bothers you then hang onto your money for now...- It's still unfinished - More summary information is needed on the village simulation side to make the user experience less cumbersome. Sometimes is hard to keep track of all the things that are going on (alpha 20).- Combat control also is a bit hit and miss at this stage (alpha 20).In conclusion, if you like the idea of early access games, enjoy being included in the development progress and are patient enough to wait around for 2-3 years for a finished product to appear then I strongly recommend this game. I liked this game enough to buy an extra copy from my wife... I notice she has already run up 4 hours on it in the first evening..."
