,Recommended,224440,28578243,"Posted: 23 December, 2016",all,Reebo,"I've played through the campaign to where I hit a problem right at the end, but that's to be expected in a beta/alpha mode.The game is intersting and fun.  I like it.  One has to take it with a garin of salt though as it's an unfinished work.  I appreciate wherr it's going and what it's trying to do.  If you will be overly frustrated with features that are not yet implemented or some balance issues that are not ironed out yet, just wait for it to get further along before you buy it.  But you SHOULD buy it because it's a nice piece of work.I see a lot of folks making a big deal out of demanding that the devs add battle pausing.  To the point of claiming the game belongs to the players and not the developers.  I'll just toss in my opinion here...  are you ready?  Poppycock.  The game belongs to the devs.  They can do whatever the dratted well please to do.  You don't like it?  Don't play it.  You get one vote and one vote only, in economics it's call the dollar vote.The battles can be a bit challenging and I can certainly see where someone is thinking ""But if I could just fire off every ability for every character at once I'd be able to win!!!!!""    Sadly this is a false assumption.  The game just needs some additional balancing, to where what you CAN get done is ENOUGH to get you through. But that's a bit further down the road in the cycle where they get into the fine balancing. In the meantime, stop trying to dictate what they develope based on your one little viewpoint.  If you've ever spent years of your live slaving away over making one game in a small team, send them a nice letter explaining your viewpoint, I'm sure they will appreciate it.  Otherwise accept that you don't understand every factor in what you are asking for.  Don't assume that just suddenly ADDING pausing after the game engine is essentially written is all that easy.  Depending on their queueing and methodology that could be a highly complex change that theratens to break many deep and intrinsically complex aspects of the code.  I can see a lot of love and sweat went into this by a small team and you just need to give them some time to work things out.Anyways.  Two thumbs up for making something I found enjoyable.  Can't wait to see where it's going and try it out again in a few months."
