76561198009868902,Recommended,224440,30907613,Posted: 2 April,all,cjet799,"Overall I had fun playing this game. I don't buy early access based on future promises, and it has enough to offer right now for you to enjoy the game. I think if you enjoy citybuilders its got enough for 15-20 hours of play, and the RPG elements make it unique from other entries in the genre.Having said that, there are definitely some areas I'd love to see improved so that I can come back and play this game some more.A citybuilder and an RPG- This is what makes the game unique. But I would have liked to see some difficulty sliders for each portion of the game. I prefer city builders, and doing the RPG part of the game was honestly a chore. I would have liked a difficulty slider that made the RPG part much easier, and the city builder part a little more challenging.Level scalingLeveling is a core part of the game. Villagers get better, heroes get better, and monsters get better. But the monster levelling can get pretty annoying, once I had levelled up my heroes to level 6 the monsters had gotten almost too difficult for my troops to take on. I had to rush my heroes around to every little combat event. Until this is fixed I'd like a way to turn off combat level scalling altogether on the village map (for everything except heroes), or don't include the heroes in the monster levelling calculations. To fix it long term I think there should be some kind of training building that slowly adds experience to your lowest levelled troops up to the level of your highest levelled troops. I also think there should be a global ticker that says what the monster level is, and clearly shows what effect you are having on it. I think what effects the monster level should be the size of your city and the amount of loot available in it. So if monsters successfully break your defense and destroy your buildings they would fall down to an easier level. This would also force larger cities to invest more in defense.Building synergiesRight now all of the buildings are very independant, they have their own research paths, and they don't really have any effects on the buildings around them. I think the city-building aspects of this game would be greatly improved if each building also provided some synergistic benefits to nearby buildings. Some of the synergies I'd like to see:Cottage provides bonus to worker productivity of nearby buildings. Since villagers no longer need to walk around to provide for their needs, forcing players to keep the cottage closer could simulate the benefits of having their home close to their workplace.Sawmill and hunting lodge next to each other. Animals like the tree cover so maybe provide a benefit to animal spawning near a sawmillTowers that are garrisoned will increase the range of nearby buildings.Walls near a gatehouse are strengthenedBlacksmith provides small productivity bonus when next to any building that it could provide tools for.Town improvementsIt would be good to get a building that can serve as a research center for general improvements to all buildings. Like a town hall, maybe the supply wagon serves as the first level of the town hall. The town hall would have research available for lower fire chances, increased health of buildings, increased productivity of workers, starting level of new workers, improve xp gains for soldiers/workers, etc. This building could also serve as a lock on tier improvements, like it has to be tier two before other buildings can be tier two. It would be neat if this building replaced the lamppost for fast travel. Maybe this building would also provide a special minor-hero unit 'the mayor' he could level up like other characters. He would be able to cast productivity enhancements on nearby buildings, if ""killed"" he would lose 10% experience but also hide out in the town hall for 2 minutes while he recoveres.RTS improvements-Rally flags for military buildings. I found it easy to create a choke point where new monsters would go and I would just leave a bunch of my soldiers there. It would be nice if military buildings could create rally flags so new soldiers would automatically go to the spot. Also there need to be a way in the barracks to auto create arbalists or city guards, right now it will default to auto-creating spearmen who are the weakest.Patrols. I want to be able to assign military units to patrol a certain area.Formation behavior. If I tell a large military group to go to a location, I don't want the cavalry charging in ahead without support from arbalists.That is a long list of suggestions. I don't think they are all absolutely necessary, but they would all be nice to have. If I find out any of these features have been added in the future I will try to ammend my post to reflect those changes withStrikethrough text"
