76561197985589039,Not Recommended,224440,15321969,"Posted: 12 April, 2015",all,WHOOLEE,"I had so much hope for this, it looked fantastic, i keenly defended these devs.BUT i simply can not do that anymore.Certainly does look like a long term scam nowadays."
,Not Recommended,224440,12196885,"Posted: 23 September, 2014",all,J-Bot,"Okay, so, initially, back when I got into the Early Access of this game 4 years ago, I initially gave it a negative review. Reason being, it was barely more than a tech demo, and not worth price of entry.3 years later, in 2016, I changed to a positive review. I saw a number of updates and features fleshed out, and felt like maybe a beta wasn't too far in the future. Tangible progress was being made.Now, August 2017, I see that the purchasing on the storefront is removed (was taken down in June), and the developer has not only not updated to stable since March, but is also having internal struggles that might or might not be resolved by the end of the year.This should be a giant red flag to anyone.  I don't generally like saying this, but I strongly recommend staying away. This game should be a textbook case of how NOT to use the Early Access platform. This shows a game relying on most of its development funding from Early Access as well as receiving many concept ideas from the community. While taking ideas from a community is not necessarily a bad thing, it has a slippery slope leading into trying to please everyone, and having the community try to dictate what they want the game to be versus what the game wants to be.As I understand, Early Access is really meant to be a way to showcase a nearly complete (beta) game to bring in additional testers, and present positive marketing. Show case the strong points of the game, and get a quick bit of funding to finish polishing the game and maybe adding a few additional features before preparing it for release. Early Access was not really designed to be a crowd funding platform to support development of a concept that is barely even a game.This game, now that I'm starting to see a potential domino effect, was not ready for the EA platform. Some games do benefit from relying on EA funding very early in development. Subnautica, for example.  Some don't, and end up falling down the slippery slope into feature creep and development Hell, leading to frayed emotions, toxicity, and a split community. Doubly so, since money is involved.I have learned my lesson in buying this early access title. I have learned my lesson in following games barely into Alpha on the Early Access platform.That said, I do hope the development recovers, and the game is eventually completed. My money is already gone, and not refundable unless a class action suit is filed. So yes, I would very much like to see completion and progress. But at this time, and for the foreseeable future, I don't see it happening.Stay away.Old Review and Update Start Here:-------------------------------------------Though ""Review"" is probably the wrong way to go about this, I'll opine on my thoughts from what I've seen so far.Having only played the tutorial area mode. (I need to try the recent updates with the partially complete sandbox/builder)  I honestly do see the potential in the game, and I like the idea of where the devs are going with it. Whether or not it ends up being successful depends on what features make it into the final product, and how well those features actually mesh. Right now, there's not enough to go on to really make a ""yes get it, or no, stay away"" kind of decision. It is very much ""wait and see how it develops"" at this juncture.In it's current state, I cannot recommend it. But, I would say, do keep an eye on it, and see where it goes. If you're looking for a near-complete playable game experience, stay away. But yeah, the final product could very well be worth waiting for. I am glad to have bought the early access to help support the developers.UPDATE: Nov. 28th, 2016Okay, so, I've given the game a fair amount of time to continue development, and recently came back to give the game another shot, and see what is new. I've only looked at sandbox mode so far, but I do like what I see. Keep in mind, the last time I looked at the game was when it was in its infancy as a tech demo that showed a concept.That said, development has been pretty slow, but I don't really care about development time frames as just about anything can happen in the early stages to severely delay a project. Given the pacing, I think you can expect this game to be in development for some time, but I think at this point the devs are making pretty steady progress.So, do I recommend giving the game a try in it's current state? I do, but with the caveat that I feel the price is just a tad high at $20, and it is still very early access. But maybe my opinion is wrong since I haven't looked at the campaign mode yet, and it sounds like they've fleshed out quite a bit of the first part of the campaign.  Though it was totally unlike Folk Tale, I think Starbound was similarly priced when it was in Early Access, and I did not regret jumping on board with that game. Nor do I regret paying to support the devs with this game.So far in Folk Tale's sandbox, there was a little bit of learning curve, but I did jump right in and skip any tutorials. I was able to figure things out as I went without too much problem. So far, the building construction and placement mechanics have been pretty easy to work with. (I haven't built any walls yet, but all in good time) Everything there seemed pretty straightforward to me. Combat with troops and the hero is pretty straightforward. I haven't really had any ""interesting"" situations to really test unit AI yet, but as long as they're not dumb as bricks like some RTS games, I think it will turn out okay.By ""interesting"" situations, I'm thinking of scenarios where enemy units might try to ambush my group of soldiers, or have situations where they try to distract while a second squad tries to flank, or trying to pincer or trap us in a place with little maneuverability. AI is important when it comes to RTS based combat, and having an AI that responds well to various situations is very important. Maybe there will be some of that in the end product, I don't know, and I haven't really kept tabs on the dev discussions along the way. I'm not really expecting a hardcore RTS experience given the flavor of this game, but it would be nice to see some amount of complexity in combat situations, or in raids on your structures, or in dungeons.But yeah, give the game a try, put an hour or so in, and if you can't stand where the progress is right now, refund, and maybe give it another several months to a year."
